{"/service/ndnp/sdhi/batch_sdhi_interceptor_ver01/data/sn98062890/00415624785/1908022701/0581.xml":{"full_text":"We\nm?.\nsi\ni'S\u00bbS\n\u00a71\n!f\nown\nwhich we are\nCHAS. It. HYDE, President\nId. A. MCHSOJi, Casliler\nWE FIT OUT\nLife\nand\nFire\nCyclone\nfla\n3\nLAKE WANBAUGH\nREAL ESTATE AND FIRE INSURANCE\nover\n100 LOTS in CAPITOL ADDITION\noffering to small investors, at from $75.00 to\n$100.00 per lot, on payments of $10.00 per lot down, and bal\nance $5.00\nper lot, per month.\nSuite No. 12, Hyde Block. PIERRE, S. D.\nAmerican Exchange Bank\nThis is Pierre's new bank opened for business September 10.\nCapital, $50,000.00, Individual responsibility, \u00a71,000,000.00.\n5 per cent interest paid on time deposits.\nOIKECTOlt-S\nC. B. COLLINS, lxt VIee-Pretiidciit\nNOAH NEWBANKS, 2d Vice-President\nChas. L. Hyde. L. A. Muason, O. B. Collins, Noali Ncwbiinks, J. E. Mallery, Albert\nWheelon, Wm. J. Muudt. J. C. Merrill, Prank Onine.\nJOHN HAUSMAN\nPANTORITJM\nDAKOTA AVENUE PHONE 1-8-3 A\nDoes Cleaning, Pressing and Repairing and has lirst\nclass workmen that won't stand back for any kind of\nwork. And come down to cleaning it as an art and\nJohn sure knows how. Special attention given to\nLadies garments and satisfaction to all guaranteed-\nSUITS MADE TO ORDER\nFROM $10.00 UP GUARANTEED TO FIT.\nEuropean Hotel\nNo. Ill Cliapello Street\nC. J. NEUHAUSER, Prop.\nBoard by the Day and Week.\nGood Accommodations.\nI E E S\nHomesteaders and Ranchmen\nWITH\nFarm Machinery\nWagons, Barb Wire,\nBuilding Material, Paints,\nTents, Screens, Etc.\n-AT-\nHatch Fisher's\nHardware Store.\nH. E. GUTTING\n(Established In Pierre Twenty-six Years\u20141880-1906\nPIERRE, SOUTH DAKOTA.\nINSURANCE and REAL ESTATE AGENCY\nli\\&aP6ii\\<\u00a3 POP 6aiej\nWill Insure farm property and country store* tu Iir8t-cla.ua companies,\nTaxes paid for non-residents.\nLIST YOUR PROPERTYjlF YOU WANT TO SELL.\nvt\niC\nVOL. XXIV. PIERRE, SOUTH DAKOTA, THURSDAY, FEBRUARY 27, 1908.\nCity Lots\nChoice Farms\nRanctics\nh' f.\n-t\nIn the rush of other politics we\nshould not forget to pull off a school\nelection sometime next spring.\nThe town of Memio iu Hutchinson\ncounty lias started a campaign to cap\nture the county seat from Olivet.\nThe annual election of township of\nficers will occurr March 2. The pri\nmary law does not apply to the election\nof such oflicers.\nCongress is planning to adjourn not\nlater than the middle of May. This\nyear legislating is not the ouly way of\nsaving the country.\nA force sufficient to move a ton over\na good mad will move eight tons on a\nrailroad or thirty two tons on a canal.\nThe waterways cau't be drowned.\nThe outlook for a decent layout of\nMarch weather is not helped materially\nby the fact that a lot of exhibition\nbaseball games are scheduled for that\nmonth.\nThe governor has appointed Mrs. J.\nH. Ferry of Aberdeen delegate to the\nNational Congress of Mothers which\nwill meet iu Washington, D. C. on\nMarch 10.\nThose snow-biocked roads in Indiana\nwere a blessing in one respect. They\nenabled the slow going autos to pull\nthrough without killing oil absent\nminded authors or poets.\nWeather conditions are more settled\nthroughout the country than they have\nbeen for along time, according to the\ngovernment weather map. The fore\ncast is for fair weather today, which\nwill doubtless continue throughout the\nmonth.\nThe house has yoted an appropria\ntion to maintain a force of twenty\neight policemen in that new office\nbuilding. The house wishes it distinct\nly understood the precaution is taken\nto prevent outsiders from coming in\nand getting noisy.\nThe Sioux Falls Critic, while clam\noring for Bryan, deems him so irrespon\nsible that it\\ has relieved him thus\nearly of the privilege of completing\nhis cabinet in accordance with his own\nideas, wishes aud taste. The Critic\nplaces Richard F. Pettigrew in nomi\nnation for Secretary of the jTreasury.\nThe 176th anniversary of the birth of\nthe greatest character in American\nhistory, the ouly man who has ever\nbeen credited with having an uublem\nished record for truth and veracity,\naud who will be known for all time as\n\"the father of his country,'' was ob\nserved all over the United States and\nits various possession Saturday.\nAdvices from New York state that\nthere will soon be a society oroiod of\nthe women who have christened battle\nships. Should this organization be per\nfected Miss Grace Herreid, daughter of\nex-Governor Herreid, will become a\nmember, the young lady having chris\ntened the battleship South Dakota.\nWhen the trains began operating\nacross the river at this place, the old\nmail line by boat to Fort Pierre was\ncut. off. When the Sunday local ser\nvice was taken off, Fort Pierre was left\nwithout Sunday mail and has\nbeen doing some warm protesting. As\na result the Sunday service is to be re\nsumed, two trains a day carrying it\nacross the river, one in the morning and\none in the evening.\nThe Chicago and Northwestern Rail\nroad company has issued an executive\norder prohibiting the throwing of rice\nand the hurling of old shoes and other\nmissiles at auv bridal party entertain\ning the company's trains. Hereafter\nthe blushing bride and the embarrassed\nbridegroom can go to any Northwestern\nstation' and be assured they will receive\nthe protection of the railway company\nagainst the hurricane of projectiles\nwhich generally strikes the happy\ncouple.\nThe attorney general of Iowa has'\nenunciated a whole some doctrine wnen\nhe says that under/he Iowa laws cor\nporations can not own and operate\nsaloons. The right to run such places\nis individual and the individual re\nsponsibility is what the laws contem\nplate. One-half of the evils in the\nlarge cities have grown from saloons\noperated by big breweries. They have\ncommercialized and debauched the\nbusiness of selling liquors. The move\nment is at the present time general to\nseparate the two and the wisest among\nthe brewers arerapidly confining them\nselves to brewing, not to operating\nplaces to induce the sale of their liquors.\nThe democrats of Stanley county be\nlieve that now is the time for them to\nget together, and Warren Young,\nchairman of their county committee\nhas called amass meeting of the demo\ncratp of the county to be held at Mid\nland on the 12t,h of March for the pur\npose of organizing a Bryan club and\ncompleting a thorough county organ\nization for the campaign in the June\nprimaries and the election in the tall.'\"\nIndications point to the fact that the\npresident has definitely decided to is\nsue his proclamation opening Tripp\ncounty Indian lands to settlement and\nthat the registration drawing and filing\nwill take place during the oomlng sum\nmer. When thn Indian department\ntook up the matter of alloting the Rose\nbud Indiaus they decided to wait until\nthe alloting was entirely completed be\nfore coulirming any of the allotments.\nThe vital statistical report from\nCheyenne agency for the past three\nmonths shows that there are yet 217\nUtes at Thunder Butte, iu the north\nwest corner of the Cheyenne reservation.\nOne hundred forty-nine of the band is\nat Rapid City, aud it is expected that\nthe whole band will be returned to their\nown reservation in Utah th's spring.\nAmong those at Th.under Butte there\nhave been five deaths since September,\namong\"them Chief Pantalfune, who\nwas blind at the time of his death.\nPeople travel great distances to enjoy\nmuch poorer trout fishing than is fur\nnished by our streams. It is therefore\nwell worth while that we use due dili\ngence to keep the streams well stocked.\nNo more delightful outing can be offer\ned to the lover of nature who dwells on\nour prairies than a week or a month\nalong Rapid Castle, Spring or Spear\nfish canyons, while to those who love\nthe click of the reel there is added a\nzest that is above price and impossible\nof description.\nEverybody likes a clean, attractive,\nenterprising and prosperous town.\nTherefore every citizen who does his\npart toward making his town clean,\nattractive, enterprising and prosperous\nIs a help to the ontire community.\nEvery slight improvement, every delap\nidated structuie removed, every weath\ner-beaten wall painted and every tree\nplanted tends toward an attractive\nwhole. Every town should have an or\nganization devoted chiefly to the man\nagement of such work. It is second in\nimportance only to work for those\nthings generally considered more ma\nterial.\nFour hundred dollars an acre for\nStanley county laud pulfs up the people\nof that county, that price having just\nrecently been paid for a tract adjoining\nFort Pierre, which has been used as a\ntruck farm, and which the purchaser\nwill continue to use for truck and fruit.\nThe soil is alluvial and is shown by\ndigging to reach down twenty-three\nfeet which makes it practically inex\nhaustible. This comes near being a\nrecord price for South Dakota and it is\none which will make the older sections\nof the state east of the river to begin to\nsit up and take notice of that part of\nthe state west of the Big Muddy. Of\ncourse this was an exceptional tract\nwith good improvements, but not many\ntracts of farm laud whatever the im\nprovements would bring such price in\nthis state.\nBusiness Growing Better.\nA bright feature of the. news touch\ning the industrial situation is the record\nof the many mills which had been com\npelled to slow down for lack of orders\nwhich are now re-employing thousands\nof workers. The action is wide-Bpread\nthe reports of the resumption of op\nerations coming from all over the coun\ntry. This means, of course, that the\nplants of all kinds are in receipt of\norders that permit of the extensive re\nsumption of active operations. The\nrenewal of orders is especially impor.\ntant because it appears to be the fact\nin all lines of manufacturing, that there\nare ndwhere on hand in the stores-on\ntfie millsHarge stocks of goods,\nmakes the outlook foi a continuing\nbusiness much better than it otherwise\nmight be. It is conceeded that jobbers\nand merchants are ordering goods only\nas they need them, and that there is no\ngeneral stocking up such as is usual\nunder normal business conditions. The\ncountry is manifestly in need of the\nproducts of the manufacturers, and\nwhen goods fye ordered they represent\nthe direct demand. People are spend\ning less money loss money than usual,\nbut the ordere which now come seem to\nbe more encouraging for the future\nthan many have feared.\n\u2022d\nA\n0\nA'\nThe Leap Year Ontlook.\nWill Chamberlain: Present indica\ntions seem to declare for a dull, unin\nteresting leap year harvest. From no\nplace do there come reports of great ef\nforts being put forth to secure hus\nbands. Perhaps the low-voiced, dim\nly-lighted revealments of the fireside\nconference, where more than two would\nbe a political rally, will never come to\nthe ear of the scribe who makes the\nrecord, but from superficial evidence\nthe man market is very dull. Whether\nthis is owing to the fact that custom\nhas overbred our girls in timidity and\nmodesty, or that men are not so much\niu demand as they ofteu think they are,\nis a philosophical question beyoud. the\nthe average mind to solve to the com\nplete satisfaction of all persons. If it\nshould appear that women would\nrather go without a stronger half than\nwads through snows and against incle\nraent night breezes and then sit and\ncroon idle gossip whilo the tapers burn\ndown and out seeking a shoulder on\nwhich t) recline a lily cheek, men will\nhave to rake what compliment for\nthemselves they cau discover, out of\nthe situation. At least in our town\nthe sweet girls are standing firm on the\nancient tradition. They are Priscil\nlas to the scratch. With a gleefu'\nlaugh and a toss of the head they pro\nnounce for the time-lonored game\ncome and find me.\nSioux Indians Win Suit.\nIn an opinion by Justice Holmes the\nsupreme court of the United States to\nday decided the case of the Sisseton and\nWahpeton bands of Sioux Indians vs.\nthe United States favorably to the\nIndians, The Indians claimed a large\nsum of money growing out of a treaty\nwith them in 1851 under which the\ngovernment agreed to pay them for\nfifty years an annuity of $73,600, in ad\ndition to #305,000 cash paid at the\ntime. The payments were regularly\nmade until the Sioux- outbreak of 1861,\nwhen, owing to the many atrocities\ncommitted, the payments were suspend\ned. The court of claims held that the\ngovernment was still indebted to the\nIndians for $788,971, which was today\natlirmed.\nTo Survey Reservation.\nN. B. Switzer, of Washington, a\ngovernment inspector of surveys, is in\nthis city and will inspect the survey of\nthe old Fort Bennett military reserva\nwhich comprised a strip of land along\nthe Missouri from the mouth of the\nCheyenne river to the location of the\nold fort and agency. As soon as the\nsurvey of this tract is approved, the\nlaud will be opened to settlement, the\ntract containing about a township.\nBut there will be little picking on the\ntract asit has been practically all oc\ncupied by squatten for years, aud they\nwill have the preference right of filing.\nNursery Law is Upheld.\nThe supreme court handed down a\ndecision upholding in Its essential tea\nturns the nursery law passed by th\nlast legislature. The law requires all\nnursery stock to be inspected and ac\ncompauied by proper certificates of in\nspection on being shipped into this\nstate, and also requires nursery com\npanies selling goods in this state to file\na bond in the sum of $5,000 to protect\nanyone buying nursery stock from them\nagainst any loss occasioned by diseased\nor fraudleht stock.\nReduced Colonists Rates,\nOne-way tickets at special low rates\non sale daily throughout March and\nApril, from all points on The North\nWestern Line to San Francisco, Los\nAngeles, Portland and Puget_Sound\npoints.\nDaily and personally conducted tours\nin tourist sleeping cars via the Chicago,\nUnion Pacific North Western Line,\nFor full particulars write S. A. Hutchi\nson, Manager, Tourist Dept., 212 Clark\nSt., Chicago, 111., or address nearest\nticket agent.\nGrand Concert.\nThe State'Band of Aberdeen will\nsurprise the people, of Pierre at the\nopera house, Saturday, Feb, 29. They\ncarry 32 performers Including many of\nthe fiuest artists in America and good\ncritics count them as superior to Sor\nentianas Banda Rossa.\nTO MOTHERS' CONGRESS\nGovernor Crawford has appointed as\ndelegates to the meeting of the National\nMothers' congress at Washington, D.\nC.,: March 10, Mesdames C. B. Billing\nherst, Pierre R. F. Pettigrew, Sioux\nFalls John H. Perry, Aberdeen W. O.\nLusk, Yankton Edward Matter,\nGroton Alice Pickler. Faulton and\nMiss Alice Daugherty, Yankton.\nr-H\n.Sglpil\n1\n\\Av\" 4-^ V-? A\nv*. rs -ft ii-U'W't\n1\nrf\n#y\nr^uet\nricfcV \u2022\u00a9\u2022W\nDakota Leads in Health.\nThe report of the bureau of vital\nstatistics of the state shows that South\nDakota, with a death rate of 9.4 per\nI,000, stands at the head of the states of\nthe union. While the reports sent in\nby county officials may be at fauk in\nsome cases a check is kept by the de\npartment through papers ail over the\nstate, and those not reported are caught\nin that way. The percentage is based\non the census report of 1905, and on\nthe present actual population would\nnot likely be more than 8 to the 1,000.\nNo other state reports less than 12, and\nsome of them show as high as 16 to\nthe 1,000.\nPneumonia is shown to be the most\nfatal disease, with 396 victims for the\nyear. The greatest number of deaths\nby months show that January is tho\nmost fatal in this disease, with Sep\ntember the lightest.\nSecond in the list is the one for which\nthere is no medical relief\u2014that of old\nage, the deaths from tnat source num\nbering 296 for the year, most of them\noccurring at tho age of about 82, the\noldest being 104 aud the youngest in\nwhich that was given as the cause of\ndeath being 65- Twenty-three had\npassed the age of SK).\nTuberculosis took 266 victims, lesa\nthan for the previous year by several,\nbut while this showed that the disease\nis not increasing its hold the improve\nment is not sulliciect to show any\n\"marked decrease in the deaths from\nthat cause.\nHeart trouble took 360, eancer claim\ned 175, meningitis 105, apoplexy 97,\nBright's disease 130, typhoid 80, paraly\nsis 75, diptheria 43 aud and small-pox\nbut 2.\nStanley couuty shows the highest\ndeath rate, with 20.3 to the 1,000, but\nthis is on a basis of the 1905 population,\nwhich has far more than doubled sinoe\nthat time. Sully county shows the\nlowest rate with but 6 to the 1,000. but\nthis is accounted for to some extent by\nfailure of the oflicials to make proper\nreports. Brown, Fall River, Hughes,\nMiunehaha and Yankton counties all\nshow high death rates, hut this is ac\ncounted tor by the hospitals in these\ncounties, where patients are brought\ntrom a large territory, and the deaths\nWhich occur at these institutions are\ncredited to the counties,\nThe increase in population from\nbirths over deaths for the year was\npractically 7,000, the births numbering\nII,097 aud the deaths 4,120.\nBrick Company Busy.\nThe Pierre Brick company has been\nbusy this winter enlarging and improv\ning its plant, aud will be ready to turn\nout a larger amount of its product for\nthis year than in the past. They have\ncontracted to furnish brick required to\nbe used in the construction of the state\ncapitol, and can now turn out the best\nquality ot building brick. The material\nused in the yards here being a combina\ntion of sand and gumbo, which has\nproven by experiment to be the best\nfor the work.\nEgan Is for Harmony.\nGeorge W. Egan of Sioux Falls de\nlivered a very interesting political ad\ndress in Clark on Tuesday. Mr. Egan\nwas, however, very fair in his state\nments and insisted that all candidates\nshould be judged strictly according to\ntheir merits. He pleaded for harmony\nin the party.\nIf he has to get^up fifteen minutes\nearlier than usual, a man will alwtfya\nswear he never slept a wink, all night.\nTHE BUSINESS OUTLOOK\nThat sensible economy is being prac\nticed, following the financial colic of\nlast autumn, is pointed out by the\nweekly letter.by Henry Clews of New\nYork.\nHe refers to the fact tnat January\nexports were the largest on record,\nchiefly due to increased shipments of\nbreadstuff?. Wheat alone contributed,\nnearly $8,000,000 increase, or one-half\nof the gain over 1907.\nBut the imports showed a falling off\nof $42,100,000 as compared with last\nyear, the figure being $85,700,000. The\ndecline appeared moBt noticeable in\nluxuries. Largely as a consequence of\nthis the treasury is showing a deficit of\nabout $8,000,000 a month.\nBefore midsummer $300,000,000 of\ncorporation obligations must be met or\nrefunded. If they are backed by\nsufficient collateral, there should be no\ndifficulty in refunding those that can\nnot be repaid, providing public confi\ndence is strong enough.\nA number of mills that were closed\nhave resumed and the money market is\neasier.\nAll signs point to a certain, if slo w*\nconvaiescene by the business world.\nr-S\u00a9r\n(ti $8^\ni\u00ab \u00bbwi-Bte\nHfS\nNO 46\nwjB\n1\nrsSts\nyM\n#?l\n\u2022if\nfi\nI'*\nms\n:Wt\n\u2022y-'i'iW1\nAS\nA\nfell'#","height":"29648","width":"20784"}}
